"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592893","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>Supported accommodation plays a vital role in the lives of many vulnerable people. A safe and stable and supportive place to live can be the key to unlocking better outcomes for people and for many it is a stepping stone to independent living in the longer term. The Government values the role supported housing plays and is committed to encouraging further development to meet future demand.</p><p>The Secretary of State confirmed in his written Ministerial Statement to Parliament on 15<sup>th</sup> September that the Government will shortly be publishing a consultation document on supported housing.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T12:38:05.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592893/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592893/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Supported Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guarantees they plan to give to people with a learning disability that they will continue to have their right to independent living respected following the introduction of the new funding system for supported housing.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL2019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592894","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The consultation in 2011 sought views on a wide variety of options, and received a range of viewpoints, reflecting the diversity of the sector. It did not consider whether localised funding would support the right of disabled people to live independently.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T12:34:31.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592894/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592894/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many respondents to the first consultation on reforming housing benefit for supported housing in 2011 considered the idea of a localised pot to support the right of disabled people to live independently.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL2020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592895","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Secretary of State announced in a Written Ministerial Statement on 15 September 2016 that a formal consultation document will be published shortly. This consultation will consult on appropriate safeguards to ensure that funding continues to support vulnerable groups and promotes the supply of supported housing.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T12:35:18.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592895/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592895/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Supported Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, following the introduction of the new funding system for supported housing, what guarantees they plan to give that guidelines for local authorities will be sufficiently robust to ensure that there are no trade-offs between different groups in need of supported housing.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL2021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592896","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is committed to protecting the most vulnerable through our welfare reforms. That is why we have exempted supported housing from the Local Housing Allowance policy until 2019/20, from which point we will bring in a new funding model which will ensure that the sector continues to be funded at current levels, taking into account the effect of Government policy on social sector rents. The new funding model will include a ring-fenced local top-up to ensure that funding is used only for supported housing provision and will support existing tenants.</p><p>The funding will be administered locally so that local authorities can respond flexibly to local need. We believe local authorities are best placed to make decisions about how to support vulnerable people in their areas and to commission the supported housing services that are needed locally.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-10-12T15:34:40.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592896/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592896/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-03","Supported Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guarantees they plan to give that, once the new funding system for supported housing comes into place in 2019–20, existing tenants will not be affected negatively by any changes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL2022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592897","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Secretary of State confirmed in his written Ministerial Statement to Parliament on 15<sup>th</sup> September that the Government will shortly be publishing a consultation document on supported housing.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T12:31:28.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592897/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592897/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Supported Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for monitoring the impact of the new funding system for supported housing on people with a learning disability after 2019.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL2023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592898","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>We have announced our intention to support summer born children by allowing them to delay entry to the reception year until they are five and for those children to remain with that cohort as they progress through school.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this work we are giving careful consideration to how we can best implement any new arrangements we might put in place, and how we can best support premature children into school.</p><p> </p><p>We want to support these children in the best way we can, however, it is important that we take the time to consider the wider impact of any policy changes.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:24:30.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592898/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592898/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to allowing the parents of children born prematurely to nominate their child’s due date, rather than the actual date of birth, when applying for school places.","false","Biography information for Baroness Humphreys",,"Baroness Humphreys","HL2024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592899","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Estimates for communities and residents are not available. However, published estimates for the number of households in Great Britain not connected to the gas network are available at Lower Super Output Area level in the attached.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-18T11:43:48.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592899/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592899/answer","Copy of LSOA_estimates_of_households_not_connected_to_the_gas_network_2014_published_Jan_2016.xlsx","Copy of LSOA_estimates_of_households_not_connected_to_the_gas_network_2014_published_Jan_2016.xlsx","Copy of LSOA estimates 2014","Copy of LSOA estimates 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592899/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-03","Natural Gas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people living in communities of 150 residents or more in the UK have no access to mains gas.","false","Biography information for Baroness Humphreys",,"Baroness Humphreys","HL2025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592900","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The department does not hold a dataset which contains both a child’s date of birth and the type of school they attend. The amount of data linkage across datasets for separate years that would be required to answer the question would incur disproportionate costs.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:25:19.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592900/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592900/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Academies: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of children born between (1) 1 September and 30 April, and (2) 1 May and 31 August, were admitted to academy schools in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Humphreys",,"Baroness Humphreys","HL2026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592901","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Highways England are considering a number of options for improving the section of the A303 close to Stonehenge, which include a variety of tunnel options. The results will be available for consideration at a public consultation to be held in 2017. However, they do not have any plans for the historic site at Avebury, as the A4361 is the responsibility of Wiltshire Council.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England are committed to encourage the public to plan their journeys in advance and to consider using England’s motorways and major trunk roads of peak hours.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:03:58.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592901/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592901/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","A303: Stonehenge","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Highways England plan to investigate using (1) a tunnel which avoids visual and physical damage to the Stonehenge, Avebury and Associated Sites World Heritage Site and its setting, and (2) traffic management measures to discourage travel at peak times, for the A303 at Stonehenge.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592902","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Government has proactively sought the views of the Joint World Heritage/ the International Council on Monuments and Sites (ICOMOS) Advisory Committee and welcomes its recommendations.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England are supported by Historic England to consider the asset resilience and future proofing for their proposals for this section of the A303. This will be presented at a public consultation on proposed route options in 2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:02:19.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592902/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592902/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","A303: Stonehenge","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking towards adopting the recommendation of the Joint World Heritage/ICOMOS Advisory Committee on Stonehenge that the asset life design of the A303 widening scheme should "incorporate asset resilience and future proofing in design".","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592903","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-11","<p>Where appropriate UK World Heritage sites are afforded statutory protection through designation of specific assets through existing legislation. Other aspects of World Heritage Sites are key material considerations in the determination of planning applications.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-11T14:35:49.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592903/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592903/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-03","World Heritage Sites","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to enact primary legislation ensuring that UK World Heritage Sites receive statutory protection from inappropriate planning consents.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592904","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-11","<ol><li>In 2015 the UN, in their '<em>Trends in International Migrant Stock: Migrants by Destination and Origin'</em> report, estimated that 64,986 British people were living in Italy.</li><li>As of October 2016 we have two permanent Consular Offices in Rome and Milan. These offices are supported by a network of five Honorary Consuls operating in Venice, Genoa, Catania (Sicily), Cagliari and Naples.</li><li>The processing of passport renewal applications from Italy was transferred to the Regional Passport Processing Centre in Paris in 2009<em>. </em>On 1 April 2011 an accord was signed between FCO and the Home Office to transfer responsibility for overseas passports to the Identity and Passport Service, now known as Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO). The transition of application processing from the Regional Passport Processing Centre in Paris to HMPO began in June 2013. This included all applications made from Italy. This process concluded in March 2014. As part of this process, all records were transferred to HMPO, and the FCO does not hold records of the numbers of passports issued overseas.</li><li>In 2015 we issued 1,261 emergency travel documents from our Consular offices in Italy. 83 of those emergency travel documents were issued because of expired passports.</li></ol>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-11T16:03:53.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592904/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592904/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-03","Italy: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 19 September (HL1756), how many British nationals they estimate are long-term residents in Italy; how many UK consular offices there are in Italy; when those consular offices ceased renewing passports for British nationals; how many renewals there were in the last year during which this service was provided; and how many emergency travel documents the Rome or Milan offices have issued in the past year.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592905","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-12","<p>Payments to generators are based on generation meter readings and must be made at least quarterly. There is no restriction on FIT licensees making payments more frequently; generators may wish to consider this when choosing a FIT licensee or deciding to switch FIT licensees.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-12T16:30:51.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592905/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592905/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-03","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to oblige electricity supply companies to forward feed-in tariff payments to small or domestic suppliers to a similar timescale as that which applies to small or domestic customers.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592906","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-13","<p>The UK's Apache AH-64E helicopters are being bought from the US Government through their Foreign Military Sales (FMS) programme. As such, the UK Government does not have a direct contractual relationship with the Apache AH-64E supply chain. It is understood, however, that at least five UK companies have been successful in securing sub-contracts from Boeing, the helicopter manufacturer and lead system integrator, on the Apache programme. Together, these contracts represent about 5 per cent by value of Boeing's contribution to the global Apache programme.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-13T15:31:47.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592906/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592906/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-03","Apache AH-64 Helicopter","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of their decision to buy Apache AH-64E helicopters through a foreign military sale with the United States government, how many UK companies are part of the AH-64E global supply chain; and by value, what proportion of the total cost of an AH-64E their goods and services represent.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592907","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-13","<p>Network Rail has been fined fifteen times over the last five years for breaches of health and safety legislation, however the incidents that these fines correspond with took place over the last thirteen years (2003-2016). All fines must be paid out of existing budgets and no additional funding will be made available by government and no extra can be raised from track access charges.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-13T12:58:10.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592907/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592907/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","Network Rail: Industrial Health and Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on how many occasions over each of the last five years Network Rail has been fined for breaches of health and safety legislation; and what safeguards are in place to ensure that fines are not passed on to the taxpayer or passengers.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592908","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-13","<p>Network Rail’s business performance is measured in every four-week period through a scorecard that includes a series of safety measures. Performance against the metrics in the scorecard is linked to the bonuses of senior managers.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of the company’s Executive Directors, each year Network Rail’s Remuneration Committee assesses performance for the year and decides whether the scorecard out-turn should be adjusted on safety grounds. Network Rail’s Management Incentive Plan states that in the event of a serious safety incident during the year, which impacts passengers, the workforce or the public, for which Network Rail was responsible, no incentive would normally be payable to any executive director for that year.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-13T13:22:15.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592908/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592908/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","Network Rail: Industrial Health and Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there is any link between the salaries of senior managers in Network Rail and health and safety performance.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592909","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>The independent Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) is responsible for setting monetary policy to deliver its primary objective of maintaining price stability. As the MPC remit makes clear, ensuring price stability is an essential pre-requisite for economic prosperity. The MPC is accountable to both Parliament and the public, through regular reports and evidence given to the Treasury Committee. The Bank of England has previously produced analysis of the distributional effects of asset purchases on different groups in society. At the August Inflation Report hearing on 7 September the Bank committed to updating this analysis.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-10-17T14:27:01.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592909/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592909/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-03","Monetary Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will review the impact of quantitative easing on investment and on savings to determine whether it is of greater benefit to one or the other.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592910","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>The government takes this issue very seriously.</p><p> </p><p>The government will introduce measures to strengthen investor protection when it transposes the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive II (MiFID II).</p><p> </p><p>This will include powers for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) to prohibit or restrict the marketing, distribution or sale of financial instruments, including relevant binary options where there are significant investor protection concerns.</p><p> </p><p>These powers will apply from 3 January 2018.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-10-17T12:36:00.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592910/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592910/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-03","Financial Services: Marketing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to restrict the advertising and promotion of primary option trading and investment to retail investors in the UK by firms based in Cyprus and Malta.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592911","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is determined to ensure the UK audio-visual industry thrives outside of the EU. The Secretary of State held a roundtable with key stakeholders to discuss implications for the industry, and over the coming weeks and months government will be engaging in further discussions with the businesses and key stakeholders.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","HL2038 ; HL2039","2016-10-12T16:07:29.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592911/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592911/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-03","Audio-visual Industry: Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effects of the UK leaving the EU on the audio-visual industry.","false","Biography information for Baroness Quin",,"Baroness Quin","HL2037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592912","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is determined to ensure the UK audio-visual industry thrives outside of the EU. The Secretary of State held a roundtable with key stakeholders to discuss implications for the industry, and over the coming weeks and months government will be engaging in further discussions with the businesses and key stakeholders.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","HL2037 ; HL2039","2016-10-12T16:07:29.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592912/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592912/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-03","Audio-visual Industry: Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what meetings they have held with representatives of the audio-visual industry about the implications for the industry of the result of the referendum on EU membership; and which government departments have been involved in such meetings.","false","Biography information for Baroness Quin",,"Baroness Quin","HL2038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592913","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is determined to ensure the UK audio-visual industry thrives outside of the EU. The Secretary of State held a roundtable with key stakeholders to discuss implications for the industry, and over the coming weeks and months government will be engaging in further discussions with the businesses and key stakeholders.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","HL2037 ; HL2038","2016-10-12T16:07:29.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592913/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592913/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-03","Audio-visual Industry: Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to hold meetings with representatives of the audio-visual industry about the effects of the UK leaving the EU; and if so, which government departments will be involved in such meetings.","false","Biography information for Baroness Quin",,"Baroness Quin","HL2039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592914","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is disappointed at recent action by Mauritius in seeking a UN General Assembly resolution requesting “an advisory opinion from the International Court of Justice on the legal consequences of the separation of the Chagos Archipelago from Mauritius in 1965”. We believe this is an inappropriate use of the International Court of Justice advisory opinion mechanism and sets an unwelcome precedent for other bilateral disputes. Whilst we are disappointed that this item has been added to the UNGA agenda, we are pleased that discussions at UNGA will be deferred until at least June 2017 in order to allow for bilateral discussions with Mauritius. We are hopeful that we can reach an agreed way forward through such bilateral discussions.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-12T16:31:21.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592914/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592914/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-03","British Indian Ocean Territory","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the discussions with the government of the US over the extension of the 1966 agreement concerning the British Indian Ocean Territory will be followed by discussions with Mauritius over the future sovereignty of the Chagos Islands.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL2040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592915","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>This report highlighted the importance of governance and ethical consideration in children’s services research. The report suggested that at the time of the research, local practice was variable, but there were, and still are, a number of accepted research governance arrangements in place for local authorities and other research organisations to seek guidance and approval, including the Association of Directors of Children’s Services (ADCS), the Social Research Association, the NSPCC, and university ethics boards. The Department for Education has concluded that these arrangements are the best route for local authorities and external research organisations to obtain external guidance on research governance and ethics.</p><p>Following publication of the report, the Department, in consultation with the ADCS Research Group, has developed ethics guidance and an ethics checklist for its own funded research and evaluation. This is based on the Government Social Research Professional Guidance, which sets out the principles that should be used when conducting social research for the Government. It states that those conducting, commissioning or managing Government social research have a responsibility to ensure that research is conducted using appropriate methods and that the rights and interests of all those involved in the research process are protected. Research should be conducted in a manner that:</p><ul><li><p>ensures valid, informed consent is obtained before individuals participate in research (for children under 16, parents/legal guardians as well as the children themselves must be approached for consent to participate);</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>takes reasonable steps to identify and remove barriers to participation;</p></li><li><p>avoids personal and social harm; and</p></li><li><p>protects the confidentiality of information about research participants and their identities.</p></li></ul>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:58:42.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592915/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592915/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Children: Social Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what conclusions they have drawn from the research commissioned by the Department for Education in 2010 into the development of government guidance on governance arrangements in children’s services: <i>Research governance in children’s services: the scope for new advice</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL2041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592916","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>We welcome the Sense report, Realising Aspirations for All and its findings. We want all disabled and people with a long term health condition to fulfil their potential and achieve their aspirations.</p><p>We will soon publish a Green Paper on work and health and conduct a consultation to understand how every individual can have the opportunity to work and share in the economic and health benefits that work brings, regardless of their health condition or disability. We will engage with Sense and other key stakeholders as part of the Green Paper consultation.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T16:56:57.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592916/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592916/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Disability: Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the findings of the recent report <i>Realising Aspirations for All</i> by the charity Sense.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL2042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592917","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Government is committed to enabling all disabled people to fulfil their potential and achieve their aspirations. Work is an important part of this, which is why the Government has committed itself to halving the disability employment gap.</p><p>We will soon publish a Green Paper on work and health and conduct a consultation to understand how every individual can have the opportunity to work and share in the economic and health benefits that work brings, regardless of their health condition or disability. We will continue to engage with key stakeholders that support deaf blind people as part of the Green Paper consultation.</p><p>The feedback from the consultation and the work that we are doing to build and test the evidence base will help us to find out what really works to remove the barriers disabled people and people with health conditions face in getting and staying in work.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-18T11:38:21.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592917/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592917/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Disability: Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that people who are deafblind, and those with complex needs, benefit from plans to halve the disability employment gap.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL2043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592918","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) annual audited accounts showed that £5.9 billion was collected in vehicle excise duty (VED) during 2015-16. The amount of VED collected varies year on year and this was a reduction of £93 million, a decrease of around 1.5% from the previous year. This figure compares favourably with the Office of Budget Responsibility’s forecast that VED revenue would fall by up to £300 million during 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The decrease in revenue for the last financial year is principally attributable to the ever increasing number of fuel-efficient cars on the road which attract a lower rate of duty, as well as a small increase in evasion.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, in the 2015-16 annual accounts, the Comptroller and Auditor General noted that the decline in cash receipts had been significantly influenced by the short term effect of giving motorists the option to spread VED payments over longer periods through the introduction of Direct Debit.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:01:25.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592918/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592918/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the reasons for the fall in revenue from Vehicle Excise Duty since October 2014.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592919","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The amount of vehicle excise duty (VED) collected varies year on year. The Office of Budgetary Responsibility forecast that VED revenue would fall by £300 million in 2015-16. The actual reduction of £93 million was principally caused by the ever increasing number of fuel-efficient cars on the road which attract a lower rate of VED, as well as a small increase in evasion.</p><p> </p><p>The DVLA operates a comprehensive package of measures to tackle VED evasion. These measures range from reminder letters, penalties and court prosecutions through to the use of Automatic Number Plate Recognition cameras, wheel-clamping and the removal of unlicensed vehicles. The latest figures show that 98.6% of all motorists comply with the requirement to pay VED.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:02:52.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592919/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592919/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they plan to address the shortfall in revenue from Vehicle Excise Duty since October 2014.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592920","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-13","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority have assessed an operational safety case submitted by Amazon and granted permission for the current trials to be undertaken. Discussions have taken place between Government and Amazon around their current trials and future plans for the UK. A non-disclosure agreement has been put in place with Amazon that sets out how confidential information relating to their UK drone delivery trials should be handled. No discussions have been had or agreements put in place with any other retailers about the use of drones for deliveries.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-13T12:59:43.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592920/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592920/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","Delivery Services: Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had, or agreements they have made, with Amazon and other retailers about the use of drones for deliveries.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592921","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Highways England (HE) held a public consultation on their proposals for a lorry area between 11 December 2015 and 26 January 2016. The information gathered was analysed and published in:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535213/Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535213/Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf</a> and is attached for ease of reference.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England held a second public consultation between 12 August and 23 September 2016 on the design of the lorry area. They are currently analysing all comments Highways England received and will publish a consultation report in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:03:33.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592921/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592921/answer","HL2047 - Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf","HL2047 - Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf","Public Consultation Report","Public Consultation Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592921/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","M20: Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of objections to the creation of lorry area in Kent to address problems caused by Operation Stack.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592922","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>In the Spending Review and Autumn Statement of November 2015, the Government announced up to £250 million for a major permanent lorry area. Highways England is developing a scheme that is close to the M20 motorway and minimises the impact on the local infrastructure.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:01:51.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592922/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592922/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","M20: Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much the creation of a lorry area in Kent, intended to address problems caused by Operation Stack, will cost, including the cost of improvements required to the local infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592923","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Highways England carried out an assessment of alternative options for a solution to Operation Stack and this considered increasing the overall capacity and resilience of Kent’s motorway network. The alternatives were included in a public consultation held between December 2015 and January 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Overall, a lorry area was the best performing option and this was stated in the report on the consultation which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/management-of-freight-vehicles-through-kent" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/management-of-freight-vehicles-through-kent</a> and is attached for ease of reference.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-14T10:04:28.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592923/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592923/answer","HL2049 - Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf","HL2049 - Public_Consultation_Report_Managing_Freight_Through_Kent_March_2016.pdf","Public Consultation Report","Public Consultation Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592923/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-03","M20: Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have considered upgrading the M20 or the A2/M2 as an alternative to the establishment of a permanent lorry area near Junction 11 of the M20.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL2049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592924","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Annual Figures on the number of claims for asylum from Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children (UASC), including by country of nationality, are published quarterly by the Home Office in the Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics April to June 2016, is available from: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2016.</p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that there is a more equitable distribution of UASC across the country and that no one authority has to care for more UASC than they are able to. That is why we introduced the voluntary National Transfer Scheme and have consulted with every region in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland on their capacity. In order to continue the success of the voluntary scheme more local authorities will need to participate and offer places for unaccompanied children from councils which are caring for disproportionately high numbers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2055","2016-10-17T16:43:53.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592924/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592924/answer","immigration-statistics-q2-2016snr.pdf","immigration-statistics-q2-2016snr.pdf","Immigration Stats - April - June 2016","Immigration Stats - April - June 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592924/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many unaccompanied young asylum seekers have arrived in the UK in the past 12 months; and where they have been sent.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592925","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>The number of asylum claims made in France over any given period, and their outcome, is a matter for the French authorities.</p><p>The Dublin Regulation is the mechanism for determining responsibility for considering an asylum claim. If accepted for transfer to the UK, the asylum claim is considered in the UK after the individual has been transferred.</p><p>The Home Office has accepted responsibility to consider the asylum claims of over 80 unaccompanied minors from France under Dublin since the start of the year and many more are in train.</p><p>Dublin transfer requests involving children are now generally processed within 10 days by a dedicated team in the Home Office. Children can then be transferred within weeks and are now arriving in the UK on an almost weekly basis. A senior Home Office official has been seconded to the French Interior Ministry to help speed up the process of identifying children who may qualify for transfer to the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2052 ; HL2053","2016-10-13T14:29:22.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592925/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592925/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many claims have been made by young asylum seekers in Calais in the past 12 months; of those, how many have been accepted; and how many applicants have been allowed to proceed to the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592926","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>The number of asylum claims made in France over any given period, and their outcome, is a matter for the French authorities.</p><p>The Dublin Regulation is the mechanism for determining responsibility for considering an asylum claim. If accepted for transfer to the UK, the asylum claim is considered in the UK after the individual has been transferred.</p><p>The Home Office has accepted responsibility to consider the asylum claims of over 80 unaccompanied minors from France under Dublin since the start of the year and many more are in train.</p><p>Dublin transfer requests involving children are now generally processed within 10 days by a dedicated team in the Home Office. Children can then be transferred within weeks and are now arriving in the UK on an almost weekly basis. A senior Home Office official has been seconded to the French Interior Ministry to help speed up the process of identifying children who may qualify for transfer to the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2051 ; HL2053","2016-10-13T14:29:22.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592926/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592926/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many claims made by young asylum seekers in Calais in the past 12 months were refused, and on what grounds.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592927","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>The number of asylum claims made in France over any given period, and their outcome, is a matter for the French authorities.</p><p>The Dublin Regulation is the mechanism for determining responsibility for considering an asylum claim. If accepted for transfer to the UK, the asylum claim is considered in the UK after the individual has been transferred.</p><p>The Home Office has accepted responsibility to consider the asylum claims of over 80 unaccompanied minors from France under Dublin since the start of the year and many more are in train.</p><p>Dublin transfer requests involving children are now generally processed within 10 days by a dedicated team in the Home Office. Children can then be transferred within weeks and are now arriving in the UK on an almost weekly basis. A senior Home Office official has been seconded to the French Interior Ministry to help speed up the process of identifying children who may qualify for transfer to the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2051 ; HL2052","2016-10-13T14:29:23.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592927/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592927/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many claims made by young asylum seekers in Calais in the past 12 months are still being processed; and how long is the average process time for such cases.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592928","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Although the decision to clear the camp in Calais is a matter for the French Government, the UK and France remain committed to working together protecting our shared border in Calais and addressing the humanitarian challenges in the camps.</p><p>The Home Secretary reaffirmed this when she met her French counterpart in August. Since the beginning of this year, over 130 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe have been accepted for transfer to the UK under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation, of whom over 80 are from France. We continue to support the French Government to provide alternative accommodation for those in Calais, including thousands of new places in reception centres across France to accommodate migrants and unaccompanied children. The French Government continues to urge anyone who does not want to live in the makeshift camps in Calais to engage with the French authorities who will provide accommodation and support.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-17T16:45:20.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592928/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592928/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what contingency plans are in place for the young asylum seekers in Calais when the camp there closes.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592929","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Annual Figures on the number of claims for asylum from Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children (UASC), including by country of nationality, are published quarterly by the Home Office in the Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics April to June 2016, is available from: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2016.</p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that there is a more equitable distribution of UASC across the country and that no one authority has to care for more UASC than they are able to. That is why we introduced the voluntary National Transfer Scheme and have consulted with every region in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland on their capacity. In order to continue the success of the voluntary scheme more local authorities will need to participate and offer places for unaccompanied children from councils which are caring for disproportionately high numbers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2050","2016-10-17T16:43:53.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592929/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592929/answer","immigration-statistics-q2-2016snr.pdf","immigration-statistics-q2-2016snr.pdf","Immigration Stats - April - June 2016","Immigration Stats - April - June 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592929/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the statement by the Minister of State for Immigration, Mr Robert Goodwill MP, in his letter to Lord Roberts of Llandudno of 12 September, CTS Reference M9899/16, that "over 3,000 unaccompanied children arrived in the UK in 2015", where those children were from, and where they were sent in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592930","Home Office","false","2016-10-11","<p>This information is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p><p>Decisions about the size and composition of the police workforce are an operational matter for chief officers, in line with the local priorities set by their Police and Crime Commissioner.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-11T14:36:10.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592930/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592930/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many police forces in England and Wales have dedicated slavery and trafficking units.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL2056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592931","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>16 Slavery and Trafficking Prevention Orders (STPOs) have been made on sentencing in the Crown Court under section 14 of the Modern Slavery Act.</p><p>Three Slavery and Trafficking Risk Orders (STRO) have been made on application to the Magistrates’ Court, of which three have been made.</p><p>No persons under 18 years old have been given an STPO or an STRO.</p><p>This data has been run specifically to answer this question and is not verified to the same standard as Official Statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2058","2016-10-13T14:27:19.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592931/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592931/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Slavery: Court Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) Slavery and Trafficking Prevention Orders, and (2) Slavery and Trafficking Risk Orders, have been made in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL2057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592932","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>16 Slavery and Trafficking Prevention Orders (STPOs) have been made on sentencing in the Crown Court under section 14 of the Modern Slavery Act.</p><p>Three Slavery and Trafficking Risk Orders (STRO) have been made on application to the Magistrates’ Court, of which three have been made.</p><p>No persons under 18 years old have been given an STPO or an STRO.</p><p>This data has been run specifically to answer this question and is not verified to the same standard as Official Statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2057","2016-10-13T14:27:19.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592932/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592932/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-03","Slavery: Court Orders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) Slavery and Trafficking Prevention Orders, and (2) Slavery and Trafficking Risk Orders, have been made in the last 12 months relating to persons under 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL2058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592933","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government has not yet concluded that it is right to lift the restrictions on direct UK flights to and from Sharm el-Sheikh. The security of British nationals is the Government's top priority. Our security experts take account of many factors in providing advice on whether it is safe to fly to certain destinations.</p><p>UK aviation security experts have worked closely with their Egyptian counterparts on the ground, sharing their expertise in establishing effective security arrangements. We continue to work in partnership in a spirit of cooperation, and are grateful for Egypt's close engagement and partnership. We look forward to achieving the return of flights once we can be assured that the necessary security environment can be sustained.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-12T16:31:44.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592933/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592933/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-03","Egypt: Aviation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 19 September (HL1630), when flights between the UK and Sharm el-Sheikh will resume.","false","Biography information for Lord Stone of Blackheath",,"Lord Stone of Blackheath","HL2059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592934","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-17","<p>We accept that our failure for many years not to build enough homes has serious consequences. House prices have risen faster then incomes; while renters are paying, on average 50 per cent of their income in rent which makes saving for a deposit all the more difficult. This means that the dream of home ownership is further away for younger people today when compared to previous generations.</p><p>This Government is committed to solving the housing crisis by every means possible. That means taking action to ensure that we build more homes in this country. We have doubled the housing budget to almost £20 billion over the next five years, including £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable homes by 2021.</p><p>We have also taken steps to help people on the path to home ownership. Our Help to Buy: Equity Loan has helped over 91,000 households to buy a new-build home since the scheme was introduced in 2013. 81 per cent of these sales have gone to first-time buyers.</p><p>But we recognise the need to go further. That’s why we launched the £3 billion Home Building Fund that will help deliver 225,000 badly-needed new homes on sites throughout England. Further measures will be included in a Housing White Paper later this autumn.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-10-17T14:47:03.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592934/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592934/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-03","Housing: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the claim by the Intergenerational Foundation that high house prices increased segregation in society.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592935","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>We are helping women to return to the workforce after they have had children through the support provided by Jobcentre Plus. Work Coaches provide personalised support, tailored to meet the needs and requirements of parents, helping them to find work that fits with their individual circumstances. The Flexible Support Fund allows Work Coaches to address barriers to employment and support parents into work. This can be used in a variety of ways including paying for travel and childcare to allow parents to undertake training, attend interviews or start work.</p><p> </p><p>We are also putting in place a new package of government support that will make childcare more affordable and more accessible. This will build on the support already offered and will mean more parents have choice, security and peace of mind when it comes to being in work and supporting their family.</p><p> </p><p>Parents on Universal Credit have been offered more generous support from 11 April 2016, where they are able to claim up to 85% of childcare costs, compared to 70% previously. This is up to a monthly limit of £646 for one child or £1,108 for two or more children, up to the age of 16.</p><p> </p><p>The Government currently offers 15 hours of free childcare for all three and four year olds and some of the most disadvantaged two year olds in England. From September 2017, this free childcare offer will be doubled for working parents of three and four year olds in England from 15 to 30 hours per week.</p><p> </p><p>We are also introducing Tax-Free Childcare, which will be available to around two million households to help pay for childcare costs from early 2017. For every £8 parents pay into an online account, the Government will pay £2 – up to a maximum contribution of £2,000 per child each year, for children aged up to 12. Parents of disabled children will receive extra support worth up to £4,000 per year per child, until their child is 17.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-17T16:58:00.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592935/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592935/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-03","Working Mothers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support structure they have put in place for women who are returning to the workforce after they have had children.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592936","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>We are determined to keep children safe in and out of school and have made it very clear that it is an offence to operate an unregistered independent school. In January 2016, we announced funding for Ofsted to establish a dedicated team of specialist inspectors to investigate such settings and since that time, there has been a significant escalation of Ofsted investigations.</p><p>The Department for Education and Ofsted are working closely with local authorities to identify and tackle illegal schools, and close collaboration has resulted in the closure of many such settings.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:24:57.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592936/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Schools: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to help the Local Government Association prevent children being taught in illegal schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592937","Department of Health","false","2016-10-13","<p>The United Kingdom’s voluntary scheme for colour coded front of pack nutrition labelling has been developed in compliance with Regulation (EU) 1169/2011 on the provision of food information to consumers, but the regulation does not permit national mandatory front of pack labelling.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-13T11:03:30.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592937/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592937/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-03","Food: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of calls for food manufacturers to be forced to put traffic-light nutrition labels on the front of packs.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592938","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>It is important that there is clarity about the roles that school nurses should, and should not, take on. That is why Public Health England (PHE) and its partners published a model specification for commissioning services for 0-19, in order to help inform decisions around the commissioning of the school nursing service and integrated services for school-aged children and young people.</p><p>PHE has also developed a number of professional pathways and guidance to support local delivery of school nursing services, including safeguarding. This guidance is currently being reviewed by partners, including National Health Service England (NHSE), and is expected to be published in early-spring 2017.</p><p>Adoption of technology is one way of addressing the burden of paperwork. Many services are now using technology and digital platforms to improve productivity and access, particularly for young people who may not usually access services through more traditional methods.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-08T13:46:05.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592938/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592938/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Schools: Nurses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of comments by the Children’s Commissioner for England on the impact of bureaucracy on the ability of school nurses to promote children’s well-being.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592939","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>Cyber security is recognised by the Government as a Tier One national security threat alongside deterring state-based threats and terrorism. In response to that threat and recognising the United Kingdom’s position as one of the most digitally advanced economies in the world, the Government is publishing its new five year National Cyber Security Strategy (NCSS) later this year.</p><p>The National Cyber Security Strategy defines the government’s vision and ambition for the future: a UK that is secure and resilient to cyber threats and sets out a comprehensive plan to better protect the UK from those threats. The new strategy includes delivering a new National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), to take the lead in our ambitious plans to improve UK cyber security and involves creating a programme of active cyber defence which will have the ability to counter-attack in cyber space.</p><p>To fund the strategy, the Government announced that it has set aside £1.9bn of investment in cyber including a new National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP).</p><p>The Government has also put in place a wide range of cyber security guidance and support for businesses. This includes:</p><ul><li>free advice and online training on the gov.uk website;</li><li>the ‘Cyber Essentials’ scheme, which shows all businesses how to protect against common Internet threats;</li><li>the ‘10 Steps to Cyber Security guidance’, which shows large organisations how to manage cyber risk strategically;</li><li>a cross-government National Cyber Security Programme funded campaign aimed at significantly improving the online safety, behaviour and confidence of consumers and small businesses;</li><li>specialist advice and support for critical national infrastructure.</li></ul><p>Industry must also act by ensuring staff have the right training, skills and tools to operate safely online.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-10-19T11:25:35.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592939/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592939/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-03","Cybercrime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to tighten cyber security, in the light of the breach at Yahoo.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592940","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>On 9<sup>th</sup> September the Prime Minister announced that we will remove the 50 per cent cap for new faith free schools and consult on a new set of much more effective requirements to ensure that new faith schools are properly inclusive. The consultation is available to view at consult.education.gov.uk/ under ‘Schools that work for everyone'. We would welcome your views on our proposals.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T17:00:04.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592940/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592940/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Faith Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultation they have held on the proposal to remove the 50 per cent cap on religious selection for existing schools as well as new schools, and which groups they have consulted.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592941","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>We are consulting on proposals to enable more high quality providers of schools to establish new schools and we are keen to hear the views of parents as part of the consultation. Many faith schools are successful and popular with parents and we want to provide sufficient high quality places to meet demand. We will take account of all the responses received when considering the government’s response to the consultation.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:23:58.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592941/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592941/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Faith Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of recent polling of the views of parents on religious selection in state-funded schools.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592942","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department does not actively police the admission arrangements of individual schools.</p><p>Each school has an admission authority to set its admission arrangements and ensure those arrangements comply with the School Admissions Code (“the Code”). The admission authority for St Richard Reynolds Catholic Primary School is the School’s governing body.</p><p>If a parent has concerns about the admission arrangements of a school they can object to the Schools’ Adjudicator. If the Adjudicator finds that the school’s arrangements are unlawful, the admission authority must revise their arrangements to ensure they comply with the Code and other admissions legislation.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:26:18.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592942/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592942/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","St Richard Reynolds Catholic Primary School Twickenham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the admission arrangements of St Richard Reynolds Catholic Primary School in Richmond.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592943","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Department of International Development spent 12.4% of its official development assistance on sexual, reproductive health and rights (SRHR) in each year 2013 and 2014. Data for 2015 is not yet published.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-12T15:34:00.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592943/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592943/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-03","Developing Countries: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of the Department for International Development's total overseas development aid was spent on sexual, reproductive, maternal and child health in (1) 2013, (2) 2014, and (3) 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592944","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-17","<p>No - the use of Official Development Assistance (ODA) for general military activities is circumscribed; ODA can only be used in well-defined training on a limited list of topics consistent with development objectives, for example in human rights and humanitarian law.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-17T16:44:48.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592944/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592944/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-03","Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to classify the cost of armed intervention to achieve regime change as overseas aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL2070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592945","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-17","<p>The security of the UK’s energy supply is an important factor in the national security of the country and featured prominently in the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review, published last year. The government also produces an annual assessment of the security of the UK’s energy supply which considers the availability of electricity and gas to meet consumer demand in Great Britain over the next four years. The strategically important contributions of both domestic energy production and diversity of supply are included in this analysis.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-17T11:11:48.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592945/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592945/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-03","Energy: Self-sufficiency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the strategic importance of self-sufficiency in energy for the UK’s national security.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL2071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592946","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the UK has a secure and resilient energy system while meeting our climate change obligations and keeping bills as low as possible. Small Modular Reactors (SMRs) and shale gas have the potential to play a part in achieving this.</p><p>The Government has committed to investing at least £250 million over the next five years in nuclear research and development, which will include support for SMRs. In March 2016, the Government launched the first phase of a competition to identify the best value SMR for the UK, as well as allocating up to £30m over the next 5 years for an SMR-enabling advanced manufacturing programme to develop skills capacity.</p><p>The Government supports the exploration of our shale gas resources in a safe and sustainable way. The shale gas resources beneath Britain have the potential to bolster our energy security and lead to jobs and economic growth. UK geology is promising but we make no assumptions about production levels. We need exploration to determine the potential.</p><p>The Government has been clear that shale development must be safe and environmentally sound.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-17T11:14:20.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592946/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592946/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-03","Energy: Self-sufficiency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support the development of smaller reactors and the use of fracking for gas in order to strengthen the UK’s self-sufficiency in energy.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL2072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592947","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","Preparations are underway for the centenary celebrations in the Baltic States. The Royal Navy played a significant role in the war for independence in Estonia and Latvia and we hope the Senior Service will be able to feature in the 2018 and 2019 celebrations. The British Army and Royal Air Force will also be involved in marking these celebrations. The UK Government will be represented at centenary events in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-17T14:40:46.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592947/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592947/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-03","Baltic States: Sovereignty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to mark the centenary of the independence of the Baltic states, and in particular the role played by the Royal Navy in protecting Estonia and its neighbours from the Soviet Navy.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL2073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592948","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-11","<p>When HMS TYNE, HMS SEVERN and HMS MERSEY were purchased in September 2012 they had a remaining service life of 11 years.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-11T16:25:13.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592948/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592948/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-03","Patrol Craft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the planned service life of the Offshore Patrol Vessels Tyne, Severn and Mersey when they were purchased for the Royal Navy in September 2012.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592949","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-11","<p>Construction of the third Offshore Patrol Vessel, HMS TRENT, began in October 2015.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-11T16:24:55.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592949/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592949/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-03","Patrol Craft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 12 September (HL1533), whether work has commenced on the third Offshore Patrol Vessel contracted for in August 2014; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592950","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-11","<p>The first of the Tide Class of Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers, RFA TIDESPRING, is due to arrive in the UK for Customisation and Capability Assessment Trials in 2017 before entering service.</p><p>On current plans, we expect all four MARS Tankers to have entered service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary by the end of 2018.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-11T16:15:00.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592950/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592950/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-03","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when RFA Tidespring will reach the UK and become fully operational; and what are the planned operational dates for the delivery of her three sister ships.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592951","Department for Education","false","2016-10-17","<p>We will notify multi-academy trusts (MATs) who have applied for the MAT capital loan pilot of their outcomes shortly.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-17T16:25:39.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592951/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592951/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-03","Academies: Capital Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the timetable for the announcement of successful bids for the pilot scheme for capital loans to multi-academy trusts.","true","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592952","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The noble Lady will be aware that the Government is investing £1 billion to modernise our world-leading justice system. That means creating a system that is just, proportionate and accessible.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Transforming our Justice System’ consultation is about the administration of justice across all courts and tribunals and not one specific area. My officials are engaging with appropriate stakeholders, including disability groups, on relevant matters.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-10-17T14:41:50.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592952/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592952/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-03","Tribunals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the consultation on transforming the tribunal system <i>Transforming our Justice System</i> is not cross-referenced to the Department for Work and Pensions consultations website, given its relevance to the appeals process for Personal Independence Payment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL2078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592953","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>DFID partners, working with the local council, have already provided relief to Manbij city in the form of repairs to water and electricity networks, as well the provision of safe water, hygiene kits and support for waste removal. Our international NGO partners are also assessing needs and planning to provide further assistance.</p><p>DFID supports the UN’s Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) Humanitarian Pooled Fund, which has allocated over $1 million for the prepositioning of humanitarian supplies for use in Manbij. These will be distributed as access into Manbij increases – it is currently hampered by the presence of unexploded ordnance.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-12T15:33:40.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592953/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592953/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-03","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether international relief and resettlement aid has reached Manbij in Syria; and if not, what plans they have to make this possible.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592954","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>No formal request for air support to the Lebanese Armed Forces has been received from the Government of Lebanon. However, should the UK Government receive such a request, it would be given due consideration, in consultation with the counter-Daesh Coalition.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-12T15:57:55.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592954/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592954/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-03","Lebanon: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the government of Lebanon has requested British air support for its frontier and other military forces; and if so, what their response was.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592955","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-12","<p>There are a number of government programmes that support the delivery of new homes including the biggest affordable housing programme since the 1970s.</p><p>Government affordable housing programmes are bid-based. The Homes and Communities Agency manages programmes outside London, and the Greater London Authority in London. A programme is normally launched through a bid round with a publication of prospectus which sets out information required for bids, eligibility and assessment criteria and grant conditions. Providers can submit bids to the grant-giving body who assess bids based on the criteria set out in the prospectus, focusing on value for money and deliverability. This allows for flexibility between allocations because value for money can be assessed across products, tenures, geographies and the types of providers. The Homes and Communities Agency carries out quarterly contract reviews with each provider to ensure delivery is on track. Through this route we have delivered 193,000 affordable homes between 2011 and 2015, exceeding the target by 23,000.</p><p>The Government also regularly monitors the additional borrowing that local authority have been allocated under the Housing Revenue Account borrowing programme to ensure delivery of the provision of new affordable homes. We also consider applications from local authorities seeking flexibility in the profiling of their borrowing allocations across years. However, flexibility is not needed between authorities’ allocations as the programme, which was time limited, is now closed, and authorities are making good progress in using their allocations to deliver affordable homes.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-10-12T15:35:20.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592955/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592955/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-03","Affordable Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they will ensure that the funds allocated for new housing are used promptly; what steps they are taking to ensure that the housing revenue account borrowing programme is fully used by local authorities and housing associations; and what assessment they have made of whether greater flexibility between allocations is now necessary.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592956","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK provided £88 million in financial assistance to the Palestinian Authority (PA) from 2013-2016. UK aid has supported the PA to deliver basic services and promote economic growth. The PA continues to face challenges to ensure fiscal stability. As the Development Secretary is new to her role, she is conducting a full examination of DFID’s work in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, including UK financial assistance to the PA.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-17T16:45:48.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592956/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592956/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-03","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the consequences to date of the reduction in the foreign aid budget to the Palestinian Authority between 2013 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-11","<p>​We are aware of reports of some third country migrant workers having employment issues, including not receiving payments. This is a matter for the parties involved in each situation to find a solution.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-11T16:05:14.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/592957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-03","Saudi Arabia: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia about unpaid wages for migrant workers, and about the return of passports being made conditional on foregoing arrears of wages.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583901","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-30","<p>For the 2016/17 financial year the UK Government allocated £3.7 million from the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) towards promoting reconciliation in Iraq. These funds contribute to addressing the long-term factors that led to Daesh's rise. In Iraq the funding supports efforts to encourage political reform and reconciliation through the passage and implementation of legislation, building the capacity of decision makers to craft a strategic vision for reconciliation, and creating a space for dialogue between the government and all of Iraq's communities. In Syria, we have committed over £7 million from the CSSF for the 2016/17 financial year towards the promotion of reconciliation, specifically in supporting local councils, moderate voices and civil society groups who work to increase community engagement in local conflicts. We are also supporting Track II political dialogue and peace building work, through education, interfaith coexistence and reconciliation training.</p><p>For financial year 2017/18, and subsequent years, the final allocation of funding for promoting reconciliation in both Iraq and Syria is yet to be decided. However, this will remain a critical area for our programme funding.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-30T13:14:13.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583901/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583901/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Middle East: Conflict Resolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much money they have allocated this financial year towards peace-building and reconciliation initiatives and towards the restoration of plurality and diversity in Iraq and post-war Syria; and how much has been allocated for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583902","Department of Health","false","2016-09-28","<p>Data provided by NHS England shows the estimated expenditure in relation to HIV treatment and care services from 2010 – 2013/14 which are the latest figures available.</p><p> </p><p>Data for financial years 2011/12 and 2012/13 are from National Health Service programme budgeting estimates. Data for financial year 2013/14 are a combination of programme budgeting estimates and NHS England expenditure data on specialised services. Data between these years are not comparable, as responsibility for the commissioning of some services relating to HIV and AIDS and related public health services transferred from primary care trusts to local authorities on 1 April 2013, and are therefore excluded from NHS figures from this date forward.</p><p> </p><p>2010-11 - £571 million</p><p>2011-12 - £642 million</p><p>2012-13 - £630 million</p><p>2013-14 - £570 million</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-09-28T14:40:04.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583902/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583902/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","HIV Infection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much was spent on specialist HIV treatment and care in England for each year from 2010–11 to 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583903","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-26","<p>The Government continues to raise its strong concerns about Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe’s five year sentence. Iran does not recognise dual nationality for Iranian nationals and therefore has not provided any information to us about Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe’s case or the charges against her. On 11 September our Acting Ambassador to Tehran raised our concerns with the Iranian Government and pressed for urgent confirmation of the charges. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), raised our strong concerns for Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe with Iranian President Rouhani on 9 August. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), similarly raised her case with Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif on 4 August, and followed up in writing on 29 August. The Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood) met Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's family on 8 September to reassure them that we will continue to raise her case with the Iranian authorities at the highest levels at every available opportunity.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-26T15:46:12.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583903/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583903/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to secure the release of Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe following her five-year prison sentence in Iran; and what priority they assign to reuniting Nazanin and her daughter with her husband in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL1952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583904","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-26","<p>We have been providing consular support to the family of Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe since we were notified of her arrest and remain in regular contact with them. We remain ready to facilitate Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe’s daughter’s return to the UK if requested.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-26T15:45:27.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583904/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583904/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Gabriella Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to secure the return of the passport of British citizen Gabriella Ratcliffe which is currently being held by the government of Iran.","false","Biography information for Lord Bruce of Bennachie",,"Lord Bruce of Bennachie","HL1953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583905","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-29","<p>The Government’s Palestinian Market Development Programme (PMDP) works with Palestinian companies to improve their competitiveness and ability to attract investment and create jobs. PMDP also supports the Palestinian Investment Promotion Agency (PIPA) to deliver better services to potential investors including UK investors. PIPA offers a package of incentives to investors.</p><p>PMDP provides technical assistance to support the Palestinian Ministry of National Economy to improve the environment for trade and investment, and is working on an initiative to encourage UK businesses to outsource business in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, especially in the IT outsourcing sector.</p><p>No specific assessment has been made of companies investing in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), or those parts of the West Bank, known as ‘Area C’, under full Israeli security and administrative control.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price","HL1956","2016-09-29T13:03:02.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583905/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583905/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-15","Overseas Investment: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what encouragement they have given to UK investment in the Palestinian territories currently governed by the State of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583906","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-27","<p>DFID provided £72 million in financial year 2015/16 in support of Palestinian development to help build Palestinian institutions, deliver basic services and promote economic development.</p><p>As the Secretary of State has recently taken up her new role, she is conducting a full examination of our work in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) to ensure UK taxpayers’ money is spent in the right places and in the right way.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-27T13:50:50.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583906/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583906/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-15","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what financial or other assistance they are making available to the Palestinian territories currently governed by the State of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583907","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-29","<p>The Government’s Palestinian Market Development Programme (PMDP) works with Palestinian companies to improve their competitiveness and ability to attract investment and create jobs. PMDP also supports the Palestinian Investment Promotion Agency (PIPA) to deliver better services to potential investors including UK investors. PIPA offers a package of incentives to investors.</p><p>PMDP provides technical assistance to support the Palestinian Ministry of National Economy to improve the environment for trade and investment, and is working on an initiative to encourage UK businesses to outsource business in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, especially in the IT outsourcing sector.</p><p>No specific assessment has been made of companies investing in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), or those parts of the West Bank, known as ‘Area C’, under full Israeli security and administrative control.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price","HL1954","2016-09-29T13:03:02.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583907/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583907/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-15","Overseas Investment: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of companies investing in projects located in the Palestinian territories currently governed by the State of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL1956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583908","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-28","<p>The Anti-Corruption Champion, Sir Eric Pickles, is a personal appointment of the Prime Minister. The main elements of the Champion’s role were set out in the UK's Anti-Corruption Action Plan and include: scrutinising the performance of departments and agencies, as co-chair of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Anti-Corruption; responsibility, along with Home Office Ministers, for approval of the UK’s Anti-Corruption Plan and for parliamentary and public accountability of the Government’s performance against the Plan; responsibility, along with other Ministers, for leading the UK’s push to strengthen the international response to corruption; and a mandate to engage with external stakeholders, including business and civil society organisations. The Champion is supported by the Joint Anti-Corruption Unit.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-09-28T14:41:42.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583908/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583908/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-15","Anti-corruption Champion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen on 12 September (HL Deb, col 1308), what are the remit and terms of appointment of the anti-corruption champion, and what staffing and financial support arrangements have been put in place to assist him in carrying out his duties.","false","Biography information for Lord Hughes of Woodside",,"Lord Hughes of Woodside","HL1957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583909","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-26","<p>We are deeply concerned by the humanitarian situation for the people camped in the no man’s land between Syria and Jordan. We are working closely with the Jordanian authorities and humanitarian agencies to resume relief supplies as soon as possible. Our Ambassador visited the area in March and we have regularly raised the issue with Jordan at the highest levels, including during the Secretary of State for International Development, My Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witham (Priti Patel)'s visit to Jordan in August. Understandably, the Jordanian Government’s priority is their national security. We welcome their decision to supply water and allow a delivery of food and other essential aid in August, and continue to press for a long term solution that addresses both the humanitarian situation and Jordan’s security needs.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-26T15:44:35.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583909/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583909/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the governments of Syria and Jordan concerning the Syrian refugees trapped at the Syria–Jordan border; what responses they have had; and what plans they have for securing food and essential services for them.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583910","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-29","<p>The Government published its response to the final report and recommendations of the Review on Antimicrobial Resistance on 16 September 2016.</p><p>In response to the Review, we have committed to work closely with different individual sectors to ensure that appropriate sector specific reduction targets are agreed by 2017 so that future reductions are greatest where there is most scope, and that they are underpinned by improvements which focus on encouraging best practice and responsible use of antibiotics.</p><p>This work aligns with the actions already set out in the Government’s Five-Year Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy, including improving the stewardship of existing antibiotics, improving infection prevention and control and optimising prescribing practice.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-09-29T14:08:33.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583910/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583910/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-15","Livestock: Antibiotics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the final report and recommendations of the Review on Antimicrobial Resistance published on 19 May, what actions they are taking to reduce to agreed target levels the use in the UK of antibiotics in livestock and fish farming by 2018.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL1959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583911","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-28","<p>The Department for Exiting the EU will work closely with Parliament on what the approach to negotiations should be. The Government’s position is clear: triggering Article 50 is a prerogative power and one that can be exercised by the Government. There are now legal proceedings underway and it would therefore not be appropriate for the Government to comment further on these at this time.</p><p>The precise timing, terms and means by which we leave the EU will be determined by the negotiations that follow the triggering of Article 50. We will observe in full all relevant legal and constitutional obligations that apply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-09-28T16:01:31.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583911/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583911/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-15","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the role that Parliament should play in triggering the Article 50 process, in the subsequent negotiating process, and in approving or otherwise the final terms under which the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL1960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583912","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-21","<p>I refer the Noble Lord to the answer Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen gave to Lord Hennessy of Nympsfield on 14 September 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Mobarik",,"2016-09-21T15:37:10.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583912/answer","Biography information for Baroness Mobarik","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583912/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-15","Profumo Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will consider releasing papers relating to Lord Denning's Report on the Profumo affair earlier than 2048.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL1961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583913","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-29","<p>I am unable to confirm a precise date at present but I expect to publish the draft regulations later in the session.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-09-29T15:21:15.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583913/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583913/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-15","Rights of Way","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 4 July (HL761), by what date they expect the draft regulations seeking to amend the Local Authorities (Recovery of Costs for Public Path Orders) Regulations 1993 to be laid before Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583914","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-29","<p>The Government plans to publish a report on this year’s licensed badger control operations as it has done for the first three years of the programme. The Animal and Plant Health Agency continues to assess annually the incidence of tuberculosis in cattle in areas where badger control is licensed for the purposes of controlling the disease. The analysis of the first two years impact is available on the GOV.UK website.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-09-29T14:08:58.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583914/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583914/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-15","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the progress of badger culls in England and the effects of those culls on the welfare of cattle.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583915","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-28","<p>The UK Government continues to have a regular dialogue with the Turkish Government following the attempted coup on 15 July, at both official and ministerial level. Both the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) and the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) spoke to their Turkish counterparts on the day following the coup attempt. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan) also travelled to Turkey shortly after the attempted coup to demonstrate our support for the democratically elected Turkish government. The Foreign Secretary also met the Turkish Foreign Minister on 7 September in London.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-28T15:26:17.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583915/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583915/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Turkey: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the flow of information between the UK and Turkey in the light of the actions taken by the government of Turkey following the attempted coup in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583916","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-29","<p>There are a number of areas of potential interest for UK investors in Ukraine, including Agriculture, Energy and Infrastructure.</p><p>Ukraine has recently been moving up the World Bank Doing Business survey (now 83, up 5 places from 2015) but it continues to lag on the Corruption perception index (142 out of 175 countries ranked).</p><p>Ukraine’s Government is keen to attract foreign investors and is taking steps towards improving the business climate and the UK Government is providing assistance e.g. with the recent establishment of an Anti-corruption Bureau and Business Ombudsman which has been positively received by business leaders. But more still needs to be done.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-09-29T13:02:15.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583916/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583916/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-15","Overseas Investment: Ukraine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the opportunities for inward investment to the Ukraine by UK companies.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1965"
