"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584060","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>The legislation that deals with single source procurement applies equally to UK based and overseas companies. Certain types of contract are excluded from the regulations, including those made directly with foreign governments. When framing the legislation, the Ministry of Defence carefully considered whether it would be practicable to include such agreements. The Single Source Regulations Office will make recommendations to the Secretary of State for Defence in June 2017 on changes to the legislation. They have indicated that they will review this exclusion. The Secretary of State for Defence will consider each recommendation carefully before concluding his review of the regulations by December 2017.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-10T14:46:59.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584060/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584060/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Single Source Regulations Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Single Source Regulations Office's remit will be expanded to include government-to-government and Foreign Military Sales arrangements.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584061","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<p>As set out in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, the Ministry of Defence is aiming to reduce the size of its built estate by 30% by 2040 and is committed to release land to accommodate 55,000 houses by 2020 in support of the Government's public sector land release agenda. This year I have announced the release of 35 sites which will provide land for potentially some 39,000 homes, of which approximately 20,000 are expected in this Parliament. We do not have an annual target for a reduction in the defence estate each year.</p><p>I will announce the results of the Department's Estate Optimisation Strategy later this year.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","46583","2016-10-10T14:42:18.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584061/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584061/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's target is for reducing the defence estate in each year until 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584062","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence’s planned expenditure, paid through a Grant-In-Aid, for the Commonwealth War Graves Commission (CWGC) until Financial Year (FY) 2020-21 is given below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>FY 2017-18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2018-19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2019-20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2020-21</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£49,908,705</p></td><td><p>£50,775,774</p></td><td><p>£51,763,497</p></td><td><p>£52,877,790</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figure paid by the UK is approximately 78% of the Commission’s annual budget; the remainder is paid by five other Commonwealth Governments - Australia, Canada, India, New Zealand and South Africa, in proportion to the number of their war graves. Additionally, the Department also asks the CWGC to maintain a number of non-war graves within the UK and overseas. For the FY 2016-17, £1.75 million will be paid to the Commission for this work; the planned annual increase to this sum is in line with that of the Grant-In-Aid.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-10T14:50:07.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584062/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584062/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Commonwealth War Graves Commission: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's planned expenditure is for the Commonwealth War Graves Commission in each year until 2020.","true","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584063","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State for Defence has not discussed this issue with his US counterpart.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:26:04.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584063/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584063/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","South Korea: Ballistic Missile Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the US's decision to deploy the US Terminal High Altitude Area Defence system in South Korea.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584064","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Full Time Trained Strength of 3 Div as at the 1 April, from 2010 to present, is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Officers</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Other Ranks</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>26,180 </strong></p></td><td><p>2,030</p></td><td><p>24,150</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>25,100 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,880</p></td><td><p>23,220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>23,990 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,840</p></td><td><p>22,140</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21,790 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,760</p></td><td><p>20,030</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>19,030 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,520</p></td><td><p>17,510</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>17,960 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td><td><p>16,460</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>14,540 </strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>13,340</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The figures are for Full Time Trained Strength comprising Trained Regular, Full Time Reserve Service (FTRS) and Gurkhas.</p><p>Figures have been rounded to &quot;10&quot;. Figures ending in &quot;5&quot; have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias.</p><p> </p><p>The reduction in the number of personnel assigned 3rd (United Kingdom) Division (3 Div) follows the creation of Force Troops Command under Army 2020. This saw the transfer of many personnel previously assigned directly to 3 Div being transferred to this new formation.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:34:55.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584064/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584064/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many trained soldiers were assigned to the 3rd Division (UK) in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584065","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<p>It has been agreed that the governance of the Fixed Wing Manned Aerial Surveillance Capability will be transferred from the Army to the RAF. Detailed implementation plans, including timescales and the implications for 5 Regiment Army Air Corps, or other Units have yet to be finalised.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-10T14:45:02.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584065/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584065/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Army Air Corps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to transfer the Army Air Corps' Islanders and Defenders to the RAF in 2018; and what plans his Department has for 5 Regiment's Army Air Corps command organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","46689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584066","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>Between November 2014 and 16 September 2016 there have been 230 Brimstone missiles used in Iraq and Syria as part of Operation SHADER. The estimated cost of the use of these missiles is £18.7million.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:30:41.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584066/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584066/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Middle East: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Brimstone missiles have been used in Syria and Iraq to date as part of Operation SHADER; and what the cost of the use of those weapons has been to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","46644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584067","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Naval Service utilises a wide range of mechanisms to aid the recruitment and retention of personnel. For recruitment these include targeted marketing, specific recruitment events and staged remunerative awards to attract recruits in specialist areas. A number of initiatives have also been developed in order to retain experienced personnel, such as the use of targeted retention incentives and career extensions. Further developments under the Defence People Programme, such as flexible engagements, will help ensure that this process continues.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","46580","2016-10-12T15:22:34.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584067/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584067/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Navy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to address shortfalls in (a) recruitment and (b) retention in the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","46687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584068","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on 12 September 2016 to Question 45163.</p><p>Our assessment of Gibraltar's strategic importance is shared by our allies and partners, a number of whom make regular use of the military facilities there.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:21:12.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584068/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584068/answer","20160912_45163_Defence_Gibraltar.docx","20160912_45163_Defence_Gibraltar.docx","45163 - QnA extract on Defence:Gibraltar","45163 - QnA extract on Defence:Gibraltar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584068/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Gibraltar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the strategic military importance of Gibraltar to the UK and her allies.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","46688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584069","Department of Health","false","2016-10-10","<p>At the age of school entry, most children will have a hearing test and an eye test. The tests may be conducted at school but can be carried out elsewhere depending upon the arrangements in the local area.</p><p> </p><p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) advises Ministers and the National Health Service about all aspects of screening policy and supports implementation. Using research evidence, pilot programmes and economic evaluation, it assesses the evidence for programmes against a set of internationally recognised criteria.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2013 the UK NSC re-affirmed its recommendation that child vision screening between four and five years of age should be offered by an orthoptic-led service. Public Health England is working to improve the quality and consistency of current vision screening services across the UK.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-10T16:29:58.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584069/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584069/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Schools: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on hearing and sight tests being carried out by school nurses in primary schools.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","46650"
